# Bernstein Polynomial Form
$$
\boxed{
\begin{align}
&P(t) = \\
&\textcolor{red}{P_{0}}
\cdot(-t^{3}+3t^{2}-3t+1 &)\, + \\
&\textcolor{Turquoise}{P_{1}}
\cdot(3t^{3}-6t^{2}+3t &)\, +\\
&\textcolor{JungleGreen}{P_{2}}
\cdot(-3t^{3}+3t^{2} &)\, +\\
&\textcolor{orange}{P_{3}}
\cdot(t^{3} &)\, +\\
\end{align}
}
$$

# Further Exploration of the Form:
We can visualize each point as a vector from the origin
![Pasted image 20220112195846.png](data:image/png;base64,)
The 4 polynomials that multiply against each subsequent point also have interesting properties:
![Pasted image 20220112200006.png](data:image/png;base64,)
For all bezier curves they are **the same**!
and they trade off with each other, creating a weighted sum that adds up to 1:
![Pasted image 20220112200103.png](data:image/png;base64,)
They trade off weights the same way with our vectors:
![Pasted image 20220112200118.png](data:image/png;base64,)
By adding the vectors together we get **another interpretation of the same curve** using weights and vectors:
![Pasted image 20220112200235.png](data:image/png;base64,) ^d82682
